{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"2a1d5636-2707-434e-90ea-e298c2ba927c","content":"Your project has a bug in `IsValidEmail` — it only checks for non-empty strings, so the `Validate_MissingAtSign_ReturnsFalse` test will fail.\n\nHere's how to use the HotReload extension to iterate quickly:\n\n**1. Start tests in hot-reload mode:**\n```bash\ndotnet test --hotreload\n```\n\nThis runs your tests, then **keeps the process alive** watching for file changes. When you save a change, it automatically re-runs the tests — no rebuild needed.\n\n**2. Fix the code, save, and watch results update instantly.**\n\nFor example, fix `IsValidEmail` to:\n```csharp\nprivate static bool IsValidEmail(string email)\n{\n    return !string.IsNullOrEmpty(email) && email.Contains('@');\n}\n```\n\nSave the file and the hot-reload runner will re-execute the tests automatically, giving you immediate feedback.\n\n**3. Press `Ctrl+C` to stop** when you're done.\n\nThis is much faster than running `dotnet test` repeatedly since it skips the full rebuild cycle on each iteration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"90728d0e-90b9-40b4-85d5-a5a7c2f46fdd","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to use the HotReload extension to iterate on fixing the failing tests. Let me explain the workflow.\n\nThe `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.HotReload` package enables a watch-like mode where tests are re-run automatically when you save changes to the code. This is done via `dotnet test --hotreload` or `dotnet watch test`.\n\nActually, with the Microsoft Testing Platform, the HotReload extension works with `dotnet test --hotreload`. Let me provide the right guidance.\n\nActually, I need to be careful here. The HotReload extension for Microsoft Testing Platform enables hot reload support when running tests. The way to use it is:\n\n\nRunning `dotnet test --hotreload` starts the test runner in watch mode, keeping the process alive and automatically re-running tests whenever you save code changes. Looking at the actual test failure, the issue is that `IsValidEmail(\"userexample.com\")` should return false since there's no @ symbol, but the current implementation only checks if the email is non-empty, which would incorrectly return true for this invalid input.","outputTokens":615,"requestId":"3410:1E6E:88E9E5:A23781:69F4048B"},"id":"1852c5ab-32a3-41b2-801e-88f394cb00e1","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:40:43.042Z","parentId":"c90adb9c-549d-4258-a59f-13f6227906e1"}
